SIMPLE: subterfuge
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Subterfuge
<hw>Sub"ter*fuge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from LL.
<ets>subterfugium</ets>, fr. L. <ets>subterfugere</ets> to flee
secretly, to escape; <ets>subter</ets> under + <ets>fugere</ets> to
flee. See <er>Fugitive</er>.]</ety> <def>That to which one resorts for
escape or concealment; an artifice employed to escape censure or the
force of an argument, or to justify opinions or conduct; a shift; an
evasion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Affect not little shifts and <qex>subterfuges</qex>, to avoid the
force of an argument.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By a miserable <qex>subterfuge</qex>, they hope to render this
position safe by rendering it nugatory.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subterrane</ent>⟦br⟧
